# Product Ethics Principles — Cursor Rules
# Status: PLANNED — not yet implemented
#
# This file will contain Cursor rules for applying the 18 Product Ethics
# Principles during product development and design review. When complete,
# dropping this file into a project's .cursor/ directory will enable
# ethics-aware review in Cursor's AI assistant.
#
# If you'd like to help build these rules, see CONTRIBUTING.md and
# open an issue tagged `cursor-rules`.

# =============================================================================
# PLANNED SCOPE
# =============================================================================
#
# These rules are intended to operate in two modes:
#
# DESIGN REVIEW MODE
#   When reviewing a feature spec, user flow, or design document, the AI will:
#   - Identify which of the 18 principles the feature touches
#   - Flag potential violations by severity (Foundational → block; Structural →
#     flag for resolution; Aspirational → surface as improvement opportunity)
#   - Suggest specific In Practice criteria to verify
#   - Reference the relevant Anti-Patterns from the principles document
#
# CODE REVIEW MODE
#   When reviewing code, the AI will:
#   - Flag patterns that commonly produce ethical violations (dark patterns,
#     tracking implementations, notification abuse, paywall mechanics)
#   - Identify accessibility failures at the code level (missing ARIA, color-
#     only affordances, motion without reduced-motion support)
#   - Surface privacy and security concerns (unnecessary data collection,
#     insecure storage, overly permissive data sharing)
#   - Check for algorithmic accountability gaps (undocumented model decisions,
#     missing audit logging, absence of disparate impact testing)

# =============================================================================
# PLANNED RULE STRUCTURE
# =============================================================================
#
# Each principle will have a corresponding rule block covering:
#
#   [principle-name]
#   trigger_on: <file types, keywords, or design patterns that activate the rule>
#   severity: <Foundational | Structural | Aspirational>
#   check: <what to evaluate>
#   flag_if: <conditions that constitute a violation>
#   suggest: <what the AI should recommend instead>
#   reference: principles/v2.0.0.md#<principle-name>
#
# Example (illustrative, not final):
#
#   [privacy]
#   trigger_on: analytics setup, tracking pixels, cookie consent, data schema
#   severity: Foundational
#   check: Is data collection limited to what the product demonstrably needs?
#   flag_if: Collection scope exceeds stated product purpose; no consent mechanism
#   suggest: Apply data minimization; implement granular consent; document
#            retention policy
#   reference: principles/v2.0.0.md#6-privacy

# =============================================================================
# CONTRIBUTING TO THESE RULES
# =============================================================================
#
# Good Cursor rules are:
# - Specific enough to trigger on real patterns, not on everything
# - Actionable (they tell the AI what to suggest, not just what to flag)
# - Calibrated to severity (Foundational rules should stop work; Aspirational
#   rules should surface suggestions without interrupting flow)
#
# To contribute:
# 1. Open an issue tagged `cursor-rules`
# 2. Propose rule logic for one or more principles using the structure above
# 3. Include examples of code or design artifacts that should trigger the rule
#    and examples that should not (to calibrate specificity)
#
# See: https://github.com/spencergoldade/product-ethics-principles
